body:
When use `write!` and `mod tests` simultaneously, like the following code:
```Rust
// FileName: lib.rs
use std::fmt;

pub struct Foo {
    inner: u8,
}

impl fmt::Display for Foo {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "Foo{:03}", self.inner)
    }
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::Foo;
    // Here are some comments,
    // which will be put in wrong place after macro expanding.
    #[test]
    fn it_works() {
        assert_eq!(1 + 1, 2);
    }
}
```
And then, use `rustc -Z unstable-options --pretty expanded lib.rs`
The output is like this, notice that the comments are in wrong place (line 5~6 below):
```Rust
// --snip--
impl fmt::Display for Foo {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {

        // Here are some comments,
        // which will be put in wrong place after macro expanding.
        f.write_fmt(::std::fmt::Arguments::new_v1_formatted(&["Foo"],
                                                            &match (&self.inner,)
                                                                 {
                                                                 (__arg0,) =>
// --snip--
```
The two lines of comments belong to `mod tests`, and shouldn't appear in `fn fmt()`.  
Although this doesn't make any difference on how the code works, it is an interesting bug.

